The subfamily ptereleotrinae previously contained five genera and 48 species, with most species found in the Indo-Pacific regions (
Hoese et al ., 2006
). Three additional species have been described since then. The genera have been partly revised in a series of publications:
Aioliops
Rennis & Hoese (Rennis & Hoese, 1987 )
,
Nemateleotris Fowler (
Randall & Allen, 1973
)
,
Oxymetopon Bleeker (
Klausewitz & Conde, 1981
)
,
Parioglossus Regan
(
Rennis & Hoese, 1985
;
Dingerkus & Séret, 1992
;
Keith et al ., 2004
;
McDowall, 2001
; Susuki &
Senou, 1994
;
Williams & Lecchini, 2004
;
Zhong, 1994
);
Ptereleotris Gill
(
Randall & Hoese, 1985
;
Randall & Susuki, 2008
;
Bussing, 2001
;
Gasparini et al ., 2001
).

Type material of the new taxa is deposited in the Australian Museum (AMS) and the Kagoshima University Museum ( KAUM ). Measurements (all point to point) were taken with dial calipers or with an ocular micrometer. Methods of measurement follow those given by
Hubbs & Lagler ( 1958 )
, except as follows. Head length: length from tip of snout to upper attachment of opercular membrane; head width: maximum width at the posterior preopercular margin; head depth: depth of head measured vertically at the posterior margin of preoperculum; eye length: length of eye measured horizontally from front of eye to rear of eye; fleshy interorbital: distance between upper margin of iris of eyes; body depth at anal-fin origin: vertical distance from base of anal spine to base of second dorsal fin; upper caudal lobe length: distance from posterior tip of hypural plate to longest tip of upper caudal-fin lobe; lower caudal lobe: distance from posterior tip of hypural plate to longest tip of lower caudal lobe; caudal fin length: distance from posterior tip of hypural plate to tip of longest central caudal ray. The longitudinal scale count is taken from the upper pectoral-fin base along the midline to the end of the hypural plate. The transverse scale count is taken from the anal-fin origin upward and backward to base of the second dorsal fin. Comparative microdesmine material includes:
Cerdale ionthas
AMS I. 24368 –001, 4 ( 50–55 mm SL), 1 cleared and stained; SIO 67 – 42, 1 ( 67 ), Panama ;
Clarkichthys bilineatu
s SIO 62 – 19, 2 ( 29–38 mm SL, radiograph only), Mexico ;
Gunnellichthys monostigma
AMS I. 20781, 2 ( 45–51 mm SL, cleared and stained), Queensland Australia , AMS I. 17489 –001, 1 ( 64 mm SL, cleared and stained), Solomon Islands , AMS I. 34518 –002, 43 ( 36–81 mm SL), Rangiroa;
Microdesmus dorsipunctatus
paratype SIO 65–182, 1 ( 115 mm SL, radiograph only), Mexico ;
Microdesmus longipinnis
AMS I, 24370 –001. 2 ( 80–163 mm SL), Mississippi, U.S.A. ;
Microdemus retropinnis
USNM 82705, 1 ( 88 mm SL,radiograph only), Panama ;
Paragunnellichthys seychellensis
AMS I. 22600 –0531 ( 41 mm SL), Queensland, Australia . Comparative material of ptereleotrine species is that listed in
Rennis and Hoese ( 1985
, 1987 ).

